result.execSummary:
The defendant Mister M Walker was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Mister M Walker is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Mister M Walker was found guilty of 2nd Degree Reckless Injury, a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.23(2)(a).
  • Mister M Walker was found guilty of Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:03 Defendant Mister M Walker in court with attorney Keith Allen Belzer.  Nicholas Grode appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Earl Lemieux Jr is sworn as a witness.  Testifies to his employment with the Ho Chunk Nation Police Dept.  Testifies to relationship with Cameron WhiteEagle and Curtis WhiteEagle.  Testifies to acquaintenance with Justine Roy.  Testifies to relationship with Jasmine Collins.  Never knew Mister Walker prior to 12/22/2014.  Testifies to the occurance on 12/22/2014 at Chak-ha-chee Lane Trlr Park.  Testifies to conversation with Cameron WhiteEagle and other individuals present.  Left matter up to Zach Quakenbush to handle.  Recused himself from the case because of his aquaintance with individuals involved in the case.  Briefly describes meeting that he attended between Jasmine and Social Services and to recording it on his cellphone.  Recording was given to Zach and downloaded to computer.  Did not create any police reports.  Went to Jasmine, Cameron and Curtis to get medical and explains what he did with them.

Atty Belzer cross examines the witness.  Testifies to how long his sister Sara had been dating Cameron.  Testifies to time that Cameron arrived at his home after the incident.  Explains why he did not prepare a report after his conversation with Cameron.  Has not really had any conversations with Cameron regarding the case since requesting his medical records.  Does review reports on incident as they come in.  Has discussed the case with Quakenbush 4 or 5 times.  Believes the recording was brought up to the Assistant District Atty on the case at that time.  Testifies to conversation with ADA Dominguez regarding conflict.  No conversations with Curtis WhiteEagle.  He has had 4 or 5 conversations with Jasmine regarding medical records.  Testifies to contact with Justine Roy and her mother.  Testifies to when he found the recording.  

Exhibit 1 -- Ho Chunk Nation Police Dept Report - P

Zachary Quackenbush is sworn as a witness.  Did not know any of the parties involved in the incident.  Testifies to how he knew about the incident, when he report and how long his investigation took.  Testifies to contact with Social Services.  Did not attend meeting between Jasmine and Social Services but Chief did.  He was aware of Chief recording the welfare check and to hearing it.  Did not download recording and did not share it with the District Atty's office.  Knew he would be able to get the recording if necessary.  Explains Chief Lemieux conflict and involvement in the matter.  

Atty Belzer cross examines the witness.  Testifies to conversation with Atty Grode regarding conflict.  He did not put his knowledge of Chief's conflict in any of the reports.  Testifies to his experience.  Describes his relationship with Chief Lemieux.  Testifies to when he discussed the conflict with Chief Lemieux.  Testifies to why recording was not turned over at time of open records request.  

Redirect by Atty Grode.  Testifies to discussion with Atty Grode regarding conflict.  Chief handles open records requests.  

Recross by Atty Belzer.  

Court questions Atty Grode regarding file notes regarding the case.  Atty Belzer asks that the notes be made part of the record.  Conversation in Chambers was not on the record Atty Belzer then sums up the conversation.  Court adjourns.  Exhibit 1 is admitted.  Matter is set for a Status.    Bond continued  Status conference scheduled for April 25, 2016 at 10:00 am.
